Here's Erlang's "identity" transform so you can see what all the expressions look like as
an AST term:

  https://github.com/erlang/otp/blob/OTP-27.2/lib/stdlib/examples/erl_id_trans.erl#L69

Building on yesterday, I'm going to walk through how I'd generate the first path:

  We expect a list of paths containing a single path:
  [[{c1, {cc1.1 {gA}}}, {c2, {cc2.1, {gE}}}]]

    These are two "sibling" paths at the top level of the function clause-conjunction.

  We get to case clause 1 with a list of paths containing one empty path: [[]].

  We hit a {case, ...} statement, and "go into" "case mode". We now know that we're going to
  build some things that will be children of this case clause.

  We effectively have [[{c1, ...}]]

  Knowing that we're dealing with case clause-conjunctions, we step into the first case clause.

  We see that the first case clause has two conjunctions. We need one path for each conjunction.

  We start two child paths, one for each conjunction: A and B.

  These two paths look like this:
  [[{cc1.1, A, ...}], [{cc1.1, B, ...}]]      % it is assumed that we include the case expression

  For each path, we go through the case clause body, but discover no expressions.

  [[{cc1.1, A, []}] [{cc1.1, B, []}]]

  We pass back our new list of lists because we've reached the bottom of these tree branches.

  For each branch returned, we copy [{c1, ...}], add the paths to the copy, and put them back
  in the main list.

  New outer list = []
  New case clause lists to replace existing single list:
    [[{c1, _Exp, [cc1.1, A, []]}],
     [{c1, _Exp, [cc1.1, B, []]}]]

  We're finished with the case, so we can go on to the next expression in the function guard-conjunction body

  ... the theme here, is that we walk our children, and then copy ourselves for each of our children.
  An alternative would be to send our path to our children, and have them copy it for each instance they
  create ... except, the child would need to know how to wrap us (i.e. a case statement) around them.
  Better for the children not to have to know what they're children of.

  Yeah, we need to wrap our children.
  I think we take the list of paths, pull each path off, and wrap it as a single clause within a copy of the case.

