Crap, I had a huge example typed out showing how case clause-guard combinations would be flattened out.
Basically, all "sibling" child elements of an AST object become a cartesian product of all the combinations
of case clauses and their conjuctions.

  If we had two sibling case statements:

  case 1
      clause 1.1 with guards A ; B
      clause 1.2 with guards C ; D
          case 3
              clause 3.1 with guards I ; J
              clause 3.2 with guard K

  case 2
      clause 2.1 with guards E ; F
      clause 2.2 with guards G ; H

  Then we'd have 20 different code paths (C is case, CC is case clause, G is guard).
  One code path per row.

  e.g. case 1, clause 1, guard A, then case 2, clause 1, guard E

  c1 cc1.1 gA                               c2 cc2.1 gE
  c1 cc1.1 gA                               c2 cc2.1 gF
  c1 cc1.1 gA                               c2 cc2.2 gG
  c1 cc1.1 gA                               c2 cc2.2 gH
  c1 cc1.1    gB                            c2 cc2.1 gE
  c1 cc1.1    gB                            c2 cc2.1 gF
  c1 cc1.1    gB                            c2 cc2.2 gG
  c1 cc1.1    gB                            c2 cc2.2 gH
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3 cc3.1 gI             c2 cc2.1 gE
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3 cc3.1 gI             c2 cc2.1 gF
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3 cc3.2 gI             c2 cc2.2 gG
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3 cc3.2 gI             c2 cc2.2 gH
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3 cc3.1    gJ          c2 cc2.1 gE
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3 cc3.1    gJ          c2 cc2.1 gF
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3 cc3.2    gJ          c2 cc2.2 gG
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3 cc3.2    gJ          c2 cc2.2 gH
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3             cc3.2 gK c2 cc2.1 gE
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3             cc3.2 gK c2 cc2.1 gF
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3             cc3.2 gK c2 cc2.2 gG
  c1 cc1.2       gC c3             cc3.2 gK c2 cc2.2 gH

  I laid them out so that the different branches are visible

  Each branch represents a different path the code could take at runtime, and the
  different scopes that are possible.

  A guard disjunction (i.e. a semi-colon) separates a set of conjunctions.
  Each conjunction represents a different set of possible type constraints.

  This is a ficticious, extreme case. Most rules won't have a complexity nearly this high.

